ğŸ“Œ Project Overview
This project involves a deep-dive analysis of Walmart's retail operations using Excel Power Pivot and DAX. By connecting multiple data tables and creating a relational data model, this dashboard provides a holistic view of sales trends, customer retention, and employee performance across various departments and US regions.

ğŸ—ï¸ Technical Architecture
1. Data Modeling (Power Pivot)
Rather than relying on flat files, I built a relational data model to handle complex queries efficiently.

Star Schema: Established relationships between Sales, Products, Customers, Employees, and Department tables.

Relationship Management: Utilized One-to-Many relationships to ensure accurate filtering across different dimensions.

2. Advanced Analytics (DAX Formulas)
I moved beyond standard PivotTable calculations by writing custom Data Analysis Expressions (DAX) to track sophisticated business KPIs:

Total Revenue: âˆ‘(QuantityÃ—Price).

Customer Retention Rate: Calculated the percentage of returning customers over time.

Profit per Sale: Derived by subtracting costs/overheads from gross revenue per transaction.

Average Basket Size: Tracking the number of items sold per customer session.

ğŸ“Š Key Insights & Visualizations
ğŸ“ˆ Sales & Revenue Trends
Total Revenue: The dashboard reflects a total revenue of $15.7M with 60K units sold.

Temporal Patterns: Sales show a peak in December ($1.4M), highlighting the holiday season impact, while daily trends show consistent performance with a slight lead on Fridays ($2.3M).

Regional Performance: The "Sales by Region" map identifies high-performing states like Indiana ($358K) and Minnesota ($358K) as key revenue drivers.

ğŸ“¦ Product & Department Analysis
Top Sellers: The "Area Force" product leads sales with 233K units, followed closely by "At Hour" at 190K.

Department Leaders: The Sports & Outdoors and Clothing departments are the primary revenue engines, both contributing $2.4M each.

ğŸ‘¥ Human Capital & Payments
Employee Efficiency: Performance is tracked across 15 employees, ensuring workload is balanced across the 500-customer base.

Payment Preferences: Customers prefer Cash (26%) and Credit Cards (25%), followed by Debit Cards and Mobile Payments.

âœ… Strategic Recommendations
Inventory Optimization: Increase stock levels for the "Sports & Outdoors" department during the Q4 peak identified in the monthly trend.

Regional Marketing: Replicate the sales strategies used in Indiana and Minnesota in lower-performing regions to boost national averages.

Loyalty Programs: With a customer base of 500, implementing a loyalty program could further stabilize the Retention Rate and increase the Average Basket Size.

